The architects saw - the office also includes a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
But who would expect a kindergarten here, with everything that includes: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini playground on the outside terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to the staff of Arch.Design since last year.
The design and architecture office Arch.Design, from which studios come a number of well-known Brno buildings, calculated from the first designs for the new Avriopoint building with the premises for its company mini-kindergarten.
In wise perspective, because most of his 90 employees are in the Babyboom-age and the company is based on the fact that the projectors return to their workplace as soon as possible.
Together with the possibility to work shorter, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees in the concept of its social program.
The construction engineers have so much easier to keep their demanding profession and child care under control.
The Minikindergarten is an original idea of Arch.Design's employees and with the support of management, they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The operational kindergarten is financed by the Human Resources and Employment Policy Operation Programme from the European Social Fund and from the Czech Republic's national budget.
This funding (subsidies amounting to CZK 2.8 million) enabled the necessary facilities and equipment to be purchased and qualified staff and operations to be provided for a period of 2 years.
After the utilization of the funding (2 years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to continue operating the Minikindergarten for 3 more years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took place for a whole year, with the Company Economy Rating providing strong assistance in the processing of applications.
The children take care of fully qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can visit children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is about a mini kindergarten, only 5 children can be present at the same time, but the day over several children changes from one to the other.
The kindergarten facility is flexible to the needs of parents, the children of all employees have the same rights regarding the use of kindergarten - without regard to the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is individual education and care, the content of the programme in the mini-kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the framework programme of pre-school education.
The children don't just play here, especially they are given excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to preschool education, by the way, they also learn English.
The classroom is equipped not only with toys and creative games, but also with a computer that is available to the children.
What is more - the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company environment.
Parents can take a look at the children at any time and thus avoid the stress of delaying the children's pick-up from a far-off kindergarten.
Parents therefore use their working time more productively.
No wonder that natural and loyal employers-employees-relationships develop here too.
Arch.Design thus joined the Czech companies, which offer significant benefits when recruiting new employees, which are family-friendly and strengthen their personal marketing through such programs.
A bone house also fascinates after 100 years. Check out Gaudi's interiors
The roof mutates like the back of a prehistoric echse, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are torn-up fish mills.
This is Casa Batlló of Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
Of the local inhabitants, the house with its organic forms got the nickname "Knochenhaus".
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile splitters and mosaics, the shed-like façades and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of Antonio Gaudi's Art Nouveau style.
The façade of the house plays with dreamy lines, tender colors and textures that remind of nature and living beings.
It is only when you look more closely that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
At night, the whole façade is still more plastic, more dramatic and the special lighting enhances the shine of the colours.
The same swinging lines and intertwined forms also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, rails, decorative elements of doors, even holes and bars.
The house Batlló in the Eixample district on the lively shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43 was created by the conversion of a house from 1877, which architect Emilio Sala Cortese carried out.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy Industrial Josep Batlló, originally stood on the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but ultimately he agreed to Gaudí's idea of an unusual and cheaper conversion.
However, Antoni Gaudí was not alone in the Casa Batlló rental house.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
The decorations for the representative apartment of the real estate owner and the use of mosaics on the facade were precisely on its rift board.
However, numerous other artists and artists also worked on the design of the façade.
The joint work on the designs for Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful cooperation between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also took part in the construction of Gaudí's House Casa Milá in the Park Güell, where there are other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after his completion, the house was given by the local inhabitants of its organic forms because of the nickname "Knochenhaus".
Others in turn called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "additional house".
It is also said that at the very top of the building was the sword of Saint Georg, the patron of Catalonia.
But other sculpture elements also symbolise hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed a central heating system with ventilating channels and typical fireplaces for the time being.
A bit bizarre, she's already mutating her 45-degree slope.
Gaudí consistently ignored all the building regulations at that time and was not guided by them.
Before the construction began, he obtained from the city the corresponding building permit but the information he provided on the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later, the city fathers were so dismayed at the completion that they demanded relief.
The councillors, among other things, also pointed to the fact that the building with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
On the contrary, however, there was no change - only fifteen days after Josep Batlló made an application to hire the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the Gallery on the 2nd floor there was a social salon, on the 3rd floor there were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
Due to the basic elements of the conversion, all right angles and straight lines were removed and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for the interconnection of rooms.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and thus a larger society could easily chat without having to refrain from a certain intimacy in more confidential discussions.
The house was also given a rather unusual roof and two other floors by Gaudí's reconstruction besides a new façade.
Gaudí's game with the light is impressive as well as the blue and white glazed tiles, with which the courtyard is dressed and the light courts.
The game of these two colours gives all the floors of the house a maximum of light.
He simply took advantage of the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colors that absorb the sunlight on the contrary.
The House Casa Batlló, which was included in the World Heritage List of Unesco in 2005, can be visited by anyone today.
On the first floor, the most spacious and magnificent apartment is made available to the public.
The owners of the house decided only in the year to this step and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous Creator.
When it was found that this is a fairly onerous business, the visits were maintained, yes, they were extended to other common and attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
The price to visit the monument is not a pappenstiel, however, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and owners of tourist exhibits receive 20 percent reduction.
This amount exceeds the entry prices for other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, try to make friends with one of the residents and visit him at home.
