Longer index finger than ring finger means a lower risk of developing cancer
Men whose index finger is longer than the ring finger are apparently at lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published on Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer.
This is supposed to be related to the mirror of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as an easy test for the risk of prostate cancer and this, in particular in men up to sixty," explained the co-author of the study, Ros Eeles, Professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help to determine which men should necessarily undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family health strain, Ms. Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Britain followed more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer, but also 3,000 healthy men.
With more than half of the participants in the study, the index finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger.
These men had the same probability of prostate cancer as for 19 percent of those men whose ring and index fingers were equal.
However, in men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, in men up to sixty-seven, by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two mentioned fingers, which are already in prenatal age, evidently reflects the different mirrors of sex hormones the child was exposed to in the womb.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Previous research showed that the testosterone is precisely accelerating the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, a leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, told ČTK that this study was fleetingly known to him, yet he did not consider the relationship between the finger length and the cancer risk to be "completely proven".
