The democratic movement in Latin America is becoming stronger, as is the support of private companies.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, the influence of Brazil is greater than that of the United States.
The Latinobarometro survey, conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist, produced these results.
This survey has been conducted regularly since 1995 and thus shows the exchange of views in this region.
Two facts are particularly visible in this year's September and October survey.
First, the good mood in Latin America
Secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its most important institutions.
In many countries on the Pacific coast of South America, the democratic movement has increased sharply (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has grown by around 6% annually since 2002, the number of democracy supporters rose from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Also in Mexico, where the economy has recovered since the strong collapse last year, such a trend can be seen.
However, only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the most populous countries in the region, are convinced democrats, reducing the regional average (see Graph 2).
About 44% of the respondents said that they are satisfied with the democratic practice of their country. These are as many as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Figure 3).
About 34% trust the congress of their country and 45% of their government. Both values correspond to those of last year, but show a marked increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
A decade ago, Latin America’s economic crises undermined efforts to increase democracy.
This may have been due to the fact that the countries of Latin America have only experienced a short recession and recovered quickly.
In addition, the poor were caught up by a stronger social network.
(According to reports from the United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America this week, the poverty rate in Latin America rose only slightly in 2009 and fell again by 32% this year.)
However, there are strong differences of opinion from country to country (see Graph 4).
Brazil's strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva is reflected in a widespread sense of progress.
In Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more noticeable and violent, this is less so.
For the second time since the start of the survey, many Latin American respondents see a bigger problem in crime in their country than in unemployment (see Graph 5).
About 31% say that either they themselves or a family member have been victims of a crime last year. However, compared to 38% last year, the values have fallen and thus reach the lowest level since 1995.
The rise in economic performance is reflected in the stronger support for the private and market economy: around 71% of respondents over regionally indicated that the private sector is indispensable for development; in 2007 there were 56% (see Graph 6).
