Red Bull wins in the F1 with a secret weapon by Siemens
The cars are improved with a software in real time.
Since Red Bull entered the world of Formula 1, its history in this exquisite universe has been marked by the speed of surprises and successes.
At the beginning, no one paid attention to the newcomer and despite his steep rise during the last season, everyone sat on the tarmac of Fernando Alonso's Ferrari last November.
Without wanting to reduce the capabilities of the German pilot and world champion Sebastian Vettel or the power of the Renault engine, the "secret weapon" that the Multi Siemens Red Bull put in the hands, and thus created a winning team, has become a legend.
In reality, this is a powerful software for the simulation of processes that the German company launched in 2007 for purposes that are not related to car racing.
This software program, known as PLM, was used for the development of assembly chains in factories around the world, energy plants and high-precision instruments.
A true reproduction or simulation of a product or process is intended before it is actually built in order to avoid faults and unnecessary costs.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi aircraft and Nissan's most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of the Siemens industry department, explains that using this software in Formula 1 factory Red Bull "in a few hours, almost in real time" can design and perform the changes and improvements that can be found on the race and during the tests.
Russwurm explains that in 1992 there were an average of ten technicians working in the racing stations, which in one season could bring no more than three or four improvements.
Today, 180 highly qualified young people are employed in the Red Bulls team. With high-performance computer systems, they perform analyses and all possible changes to the racing cars.
The Siemens manager explained that the PLM software was able to analyze and improve all components of the Red Bull racing cars, with the exception of the engine for which Renault alone is responsible.
The materials, the fuel, the aerodynamics and the safety elements are being changed.
The changes can be transferred to reality thanks to advanced production facilities and high-tech autoclaves within less than 24 hours from the virtual reality of the simulator.
The only limit set by this crazy technical perfectionism is the $40 million that a Formula 1 team is allowed to spend in a season for its race.
Red Bull has built its high-tech factory for the development and manufacture of its racing cars in a 50-kilometre location in London.
These are two buildings in which visits - especially by journalists - are strongly restricted.
Everything that happens there is Top Secret.
The workforce includes 580 people, including the two pilots, the world champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
But Red Bulls true Formula 1 - Hero is undoubtedly the latest world champion Sebastian Vetell.
Behind the enormous technological resources that the energy-drinking manufacturer places in the services of his participation on the racing routes are other protagonists, whose support is invaluable and their awareness is equal to zero.
The plant's technologist, Steve Nevey, stressed that five years ago, it could be said that the progress in the field of R & D for racing cars contributed 50 percent to the victory and that the pilots were responsible for the rest.
Today the share values have changed. Technology accounts for 85 percent of the success, while pilots’ contribution is estimated at 15 percent.
Nevey acknowledges that Vettel and Webber can never be replaced by EDV, because they are "unforeseeable gladiators".
