Sports and regulation
Tricks such as those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show inventiveness, but not the will to circumvent a penalty.
The fact that two players of the Real Madrid (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) allegedly made an exclusion in the November 23 game against the Ajax in the Champions League led to a lot of ink being shed on whether or not it was an unportraitable act and whether or not both players should be sanctioned by the UEFA.
As is well known, the two players lost a few minutes before players (their team had already clearly won) time and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since the Real Madrid would lead its group, the two players will fulfil the penalty prescribed at the next league game against the Auxerre and thus enter the next game phase without cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee punished the coach of the club, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice; it is more often found in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten but followed rules in this sport.
Part of the debate about the presented case is due to the fact that a team of the real Madrid football club (who presented nobleness and honor in his hymn and had punished his players for similar incidents) played the leading role in this, and to the dramatisation by Mourinho, who added an episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this practice, which is not expressly prohibited by the statutes, contradicts the principles of sport, i.e. whether these actions constitute a regulatory environment. In fact, this approach is consistent with the statutes of sport, but seems to be circumventing its meaning.
In this case, the damage caused by the sports spirit should be investigated.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not threatened by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid that the opposing players take unfair advantage of the counter-team. Also that did not happen.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we normally understand by misplay or rule, because the circumvention of the rule has not been carried out secretly to avoid a penalty, but it should be as conspicuous as possible so that it is punished by the arbitrator.
The players waited and gladly accepted the penalty.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders drew from the intentional fouls.
It should be stressed here that the rival was neither brought into a more unfavourable situation nor gained benefits for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to play with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club then does not have these players.
The advantage obviously is that the players start the next game phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it’s a long-term advantage, up to a certain degree unknown, as the team could eventually also leave. In addition, the players receive a penalty with this procedure and move into the second card cycle in which they leave with a card less than in the first cycle due to card accumulation.
This is not so clear whether it really is an advantage.
Finally, such practices are not directed against the spirit of sport, which also includes strategic decisions, in order to derive maximum benefit from the rules.
In this case the players did not want to bypass the penalty (it would actually be a clear case of rule circumvention), they wanted to choose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding a penalty or fleeing from it.
Although the boundary between invention and regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this matter is a clear case of invention.
I have the impression that the polemics were created as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provoked rule transfer.
The damage caused by these actions to the principles of sport is less ethical than rather aesthetic.
